Slide 3: Lecture 01 | What is Machine Learning?..............................................................................................................
Definition: "Field of study that gives computers the ability to learn without being explicitly programmed." ‚Äî Arthur Samuel, 1959 The Shift:

Traditional: Data + Rules ‚Üí Output.

Machine Learning: Data + Output ‚Üí Rules (The Model).

Slide 4: Lecture 02 | The "Intelligence" Hierarchy....................................................................................................................
The Relationship:

AI (The Goal): Machines simulating human intelligence.

ML (The Approach): Statistical methods to learn from data.

DL (The Technique): Using Multi-layer Neural Networks (Deep Learning). [Visual: Venn Diagram showing DL inside ML, and ML inside AI]

Slide 5: Lecture 03 | Three Main Types of ML.........................................................................................................................
Supervised: Learning with a teacher (Labeled data). Example: Spam Detection.

Unsupervised: Finding hidden patterns (Unlabeled data). Example: Customer Grouping.

Reinforcement: Learning by trial and error (Rewards/Penalties). Example: Gaming AI.

Slide 6: Lecture 04 | Batch vs. Online Learning........................................................................................................................................................
Batch (Offline): Learns from the whole dataset at once. Good for static data.

Online (Incremental): Learns from data "on the fly." Best for stock prices and live streams.

Slide 7: Lecture 05 | Memory vs. Logic.....................................................................................................................................
Instance-Based (Lazy): Remembers all examples and compares new data to them (e.g., k-NN).

Model-Based (Eager): Builds a mathematical formula (e.g., Linear Regression). Fast at predicting!

Slide 8: Lecture 06 | Why ML Fails? (Challenges)....................................................................................................................
Data Issues: Insufficient data, poor quality, or "Garbage In, Garbage Out."

Algorithm Issues: * Overfitting: Learning the noise, not the pattern.

Underfitting: Being too simple to see the pattern.

